    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "Which of the following has most acidic Hydrogen ?\n",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "Propanoic acid\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "Dichloroacetic acid\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "Trichloroacetic acid\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "Chloroacetic acid"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Trichloroacetic acid (Option C) is the strongest acid. Here’s why:</p>\n\n<p>Electron-withdrawing effect  </p>\n\n\n<p><p>Chlorine atoms pull electron density away from the –COOH group, stabilizing the conjugate base (the carboxylate anion).  </p></p>\n<p><p>More Cl → greater stabilization → stronger acid.</p></p>\n\n\n<p>Comparative pKa values  </p>\n\n\n<p><p>Propanoic acid, CH₃CH₂COOH: pKa ≈ 4.87  </p></p>\n<p><p>Chloroacetic acid, ClCH₂COOH: pKa ≈ 2.86  </p></p>\n<p><p>Dichloroacetic acid, Cl₂CHCOOH: pKa ≈ 1.25  </p></p>\n<p><p>Trichloroacetic acid, CCl₃COOH: pKa ≈ 0.66  </p></p>\n\n<p>Since trichloroacetic acid has the lowest pKa, it donates its proton most readily and is thus the most acidic.</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2025,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2025",
    "difficulty": null
  },
