    "yearKey": "kcet-2019",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "Lower members of aliphatic carboxylic acid are soluble in water. This is due to\n",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "formation of hydrogen bonds with water\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": " due to London forces\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "water is non electrolyte\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": " van der-Waal's interaction with water molecules"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The lower members of the aliphatic carboxylic acid family, specifically those with carbon chains up to C4, are highly soluble in water. This high solubility is primarily attributed to the formation of hydrogen bonds between the carboxyl group (COOH) of the acid and water molecules.</p>",
